314 The Jeake Family of Rye, 1640-1736

Also I give to my said daughter Barbara my diamond ring with three stones and four sparks which was her Grandmothers, my diamond earrings, my silver coffee pot, one large wrought silver salver, the bed covering and Furniture of the room wherein she lyes, my wedding ring with which I was marryed to her Father Mr Jeake with a latin poesie” and one double Rose Noble peice of Gold to be paid and delivered to her the said Barbara by my executors within one month next after my decease. Item I give and bequeath unto my daughter Philadelphia Tucker the summe of seven hundred pounds of lawfull money of Great Britain (exclusive of the summe of five hundred pounds given and bequeathed to her by the last Will and Testament of her father my late husband Mr Tucker) which together make one thousand two hundred pounds payable to her. Also I give and bequeath to my said daughter Philadelphia Tucker my repeating Gold Watch with the chain and seal, my pearl necklace, my wedding ring with which I was marryed to her Father poesie No 9: 1703*, my mothers wedding ring to my Father with a Latin poesie, one silver salver marked I * N and the Bed and furniture thereof two pillows and white quilt in the new Building to be paid and delivered to her by my Executors within one month next after my decease. Item I give and bequeath unto my said daughters Barbara and Philladelphia all and singular my wearing apparel, my silver Tea kettle and silver lamp my silver Tea pott and Lamp silver Milk pott with the Case Cannister Sugar Dish, twelve gilt Silver spoons, Tongs, Strainer and all and singular any China Ware of what nature or kind soever equally to be divided between them. Item I give and bequeath unto my said son Samuel Jeake To my son Joseph Tucker and my said daughters Barbara and Philadelphia all and singular my Linnen and pewter of what nature or kind soever to be equally divided between them. Item I give and forgive unto my said sons Samuel Jeake and Joseph Tucker and my said daughters Barbara Jeake and Philladelphia Tucker all such moneys as I may claime a right to for their or either their Board, Cloathing or Education since the decease of their respective Fathers and all such moneys as I can or lawfully may demand or take of them or any or either of them at the time of my decease. Item I give and devise unto my said son Joseph Tucker all that my Messuage or Tenement with the Backside and appurtenances thereunto belonging commonly called or known by the name of the Red Cross situate lying and being in the Watchbell Street in Rye aforesaid now or late in the Tenure or occupation of Richard [word illegible] or his assigns To have and to hold the said Messuage or Tenement and premises with the appurtenances unto my said son Joseph Tucker and to his heirs and assigns

* A verse, probably inscribed on the inside of the ring. *The date of Elizabeth and Joseph’s marriage.
